10. Absolute vs Relative URL
Absolute URL

Full web address:

<a href="https://www.google.com">
    Google
</a>
Relative URL

Points to another file in your project:

<a href="about.html">
    About Page
</a>

1. Difference between <b> and <strong>
<b>	<strong>
Makes text bold visually.	Indicates that the text is important.
No semantic meaning.	Has semantic meaning.
Used for styling only.	Used for importance and accessibility.

Example:

<b>Java Developer</b>
<strong>Important Notice</strong>

Interview Answer:

<b> only makes text bold, whereas <strong> makes text bold and also indicates that the content is important. <strong> is preferred in modern HTML because it provides semantic meaning.

2. Difference between <i> and <em>
<i>	<em>
Displays text in italic style.	Emphasizes the text.
Visual formatting only.	Semantic meaning.
Used for styling.	Used to stress or emphasize content.

Example:

<i>HTML</i>
<em>Read Carefully</em>

Interview Answer:

<i> is used only to display text in italics, while <em> is used to emphasize text and has semantic meaning. Screen readers may give extra emphasis to <em> content.

3. What is the purpose of href?

The href (Hypertext Reference) attribute specifies the destination URL of a link.

Example:

<a href="https://www.google.com">Google</a>

Interview Answer:

The href attribute defines the URL or destination that the browser should navigate to when a user clicks a hyperlink.

4. What does target="_blank" do?

It opens the linked page in a new browser tab or window.

Example:

<a href="https://www.google.com" target="_blank">
    Google
</a>

Interview Answer:

target="_blank" opens the linked document in a new browser tab, allowing users to stay on the current page while viewing the linked content.

5. Difference between Absolute URL and Relative URL
Absolute URL

Contains the complete web address.

<a href="https://www.google.com">Google</a>
Relative URL

Contains the path to a file within the same project.

<a href="about.html">About</a>
Absolute URL	Relative URL
Full web address.	Path relative to current page.
Includes protocol (https://).	Does not include domain name.
Used for external websites.	Used for internal project pages.

Interview Answer:

An absolute URL contains the complete address of a resource, including the protocol and domain name. A relative URL specifies the location of a resource relative to the current page and is commonly used for navigation within the same website.

